body:
The new WebAssembly.Global semantics don't seem to be implemented in Safari or Edge, and they are only shipped recently in Chrome 69 and Firefox 62. Seems like Node 10.11 uses V8 6.8, which doesn't support WebAssembly.Global, but instead uses the semantics that webpack tests use. I don't think it makes much sense to polyfill WebAssembly.Global during this current transition, but instead to forward through the export that comes from the underlying implementation.

I'm not sure if there's any particular change we would make in the implementation, maybe just the tests to permit *either* the bare number *or* WebAssembly.Global. I downloaded Node 11 nightly, which uses V8 7.0, and ran the tests that involved using an exported WebAssembly global. Indeed, the tests that failed were the ones checking the actual exported global value, since it changed from a Number to a WebAssembly.Global object, in an apparently spec-compliant way.

One test failed due to apparently invalid WebAssembly, which I noted at https://github.com/webpack/webpack/pull/7467/files#r223454525 . Once that's fixed, I'd be happy to upload a PR with updated tests, of this style (taking wasm/imported-global-preserve-ordering as an example):

```js
it("should preserve the ordering of globals", function() {
        return import("./module.wat").then(function(e) {
                if (WebAssembly.Global) {
                        expect(e.c.constructor).toBe(WebAssembly.Global);
                        expect(e.d.constructor).toBe(WebAssembly.Global);

                        expect(+e.c).toBe(3);
                        expect(+e.d).toBe(4);
                } else {
                        expect(e.c).toBe(3);
                        expect(e.d).toBe(4);
                }
        });
});
```

(This test passes on Node 11)
